TinyCC license for SecureOS
===========================

TinyCC is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License, version 2.1
(LGPL-2.1). The authoritative text ships with the submodule:

    vendor/tinycc/tinycc/COPYING

Decision record (in-OS toolchain plan, 2026-05-28)
--------------------------------------------------

SecureOS deliberately selected TinyCC despite its LGPL terms being more
restrictive than the project's other vendored dependency (BearSSL, MIT). The
trade-off was made consciously:

  * TinyCC is the only small, self-contained C compiler that performs
    compile + assemble + link in one process. SecureOS cannot spawn separate
    assembler/linker stages, so a multi-binary GCC/Clang toolchain is not an
    option, and chibicc (MIT) would require additionally porting an assembler
    and a linker.

  * LGPL obligations that apply when TinyCC is statically linked into a shipped
    SecureOS image:
      - The combined work may be distributed, but recipients must be able to
        relink against a modified TinyCC. In practice this means shipping the
        TinyCC object files (or this pinned source) and the SecureOS-side
        object files needed to relink.
      - Any modifications to TinyCC's own source must be made available under
        the LGPL.

  * The fallback, if these obligations become unacceptable for a given
    distribution channel, is to switch the compiler backend to chibicc (MIT)
    and absorb the cost of porting an assembler + linker. This is recorded as
    an open question in the plan rather than chosen now.

The `vendor/tinycc/tinycc/RELICENSING` file records which contributors have
agreed to relicense their contributions under MIT; it does not, on its own,
make the whole of TinyCC MIT-licensed.
